name: JsObject
comment:
Proxies a JavaScript object to Dart.

The properties of the JavaScript object are accessible via the [] and []= operators. Methods are callable via dart-js.JsObject.callMethod.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-js.JsObject.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

constructors.comment: Constructs a new JavaScript object from dart-js.JsObject.JsObject-.constructor and returns a proxy to it.

fromBrowserObject.name: fromBrowserObject
fromBrowserObject.comment:
Constructs a dart-js.JsObject that proxies a native Dart object; for expert use only.

Use this constructor only if you wish to get access to JavaScript properties attached to a browser host object, such as a Node or Blob, that is normally automatically converted into a native Dart object.

An exception will be thrown if dart-js.JsObject.JsObject-fromBrowserObject.object either is null or has the type bool, num, or String.

jsify.name: jsify
jsify.comment:
Recursively converts a JSON-like collection of Dart objects to a collection of JavaScript objects and returns a dart-js.JsObject proxy to it.

dart-js.JsObject.JsObject-jsify.object must be a dart-core.Map or dart-core.Iterable, the contents of which are also converted. Maps and Iterables are copied to a new JavaScript object. Primitives and other transferrable values are directly converted to their JavaScript type, and all other objects are proxied.

[].comment:
Returns the value associated with dart-js.JsObject.[].property from the proxied JavaScript object.

The type of dart-js.JsObject.[].property must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

[]=.comment:
Sets the value associated with dart-js.JsObject.[]=.property on the proxied JavaScript object.

The type of dart-js.JsObject.[]=.property must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-js.JsObject.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-js.JsObject.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

hasProperty.name: hasProperty
hasProperty.comment:
Returns true if the JavaScript object contains the specified property either directly or though its prototype chain.

This is the equivalent of the in operator in JavaScript.

deleteProperty.name: deleteProperty
deleteProperty.comment:
Removes dart-js.JsObject.deleteProperty.property from the JavaScript object.

This is the equivalent of the delete operator in JavaScript.

instanceof.name: instanceof
instanceof.comment:
Returns true if the JavaScript object has dart-js.JsObject.instanceof.type in its prototype chain.

This is the equivalent of the instanceof operator in JavaScript.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns the result of the JavaScript objects toString method.

callMethod.name: callMethod
callMethod.comment:
Calls dart-js.JsObject.callMethod.method on the JavaScript object with the arguments dart-js.JsObject.callMethod.args and returns the result.

The type of dart-js.JsObject.callMethod.method must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-js.JsObject.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-js.JsObject.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-js.JsObject.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-js.JsObject.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
